{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "CodeReview",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Data/BattleData.cs",
      "description": "The comment is confusing.\r\nFrom what I understand, this is data for each unit which use in the combat (which is a hero).\r\nA unit = any hero don't matter which team it is.\r\n\r\nThen, there is additional comment like on 22 and 23, they're really confusing. \r\nMaybe we need a standard for the comment? So the comment is easier to read.\r\n\r\nIs that make sense?\r\nAlso could you answer directly to the code tour comment?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** Your read is correct — `UnitCombatData` is the projected combat data for any fielded unit, hero or enemy, the moment `HeroData.ToCombatData(team)` runs; \"unit\" and \"hero\" are the same entity at different pipeline stages (HeroData = authored asset, UnitCombatData = one-shot projection of it, Combatant = the runtime state built from that). That HeroData→UnitCombatData→Combatant chain is exactly what's confusing without it spelled out once.\r\n\r\nLines 22-23 specifically explain a WHY, not a WHAT: `Tint` is pre-resolved to the correct side's color right here, so nothing downstream ever has to check `Team` and branch to pick a color. That's a legitimate comment per this project's own rule (comment the why, not the what) — it's just terse enough that it assumes the reader already knows what \"the fighting side\" refers to.\r\n\r\nAgreed on a standard — I'd add a short \"Comment Conventions\" section to `best-practices.md` (already the home for project-critical patterns) rather than a new doc, covering: (1) always name the *pipeline stage* a comment talks about (HeroData vs UnitCombatData vs Combatant) instead of just saying \"unit\", and (2) lead a why-comment with the one-word noun the reader needs first. This is a decision for you, not something I'll do unprompted.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** Added a \"Comment Conventions\" section to `best-practices.md`. Also, the three pipeline-stage classes this comment was confused about are now named for exactly what they are: `HeroDataSO` (authored), `HeroDataSeed` (one-time transfer object), `HeroDataRuntime` (mutable sim state) — see `.tours/deferred-design-questions.tour`'s last step for the full naming decision. `BattleData.cs`'s header comment on `HeroDataSeed` was rewritten to name the pipeline stage explicitly rather than say \"unit\"."
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Data/HeroDataSO.cs",
      "description": "This is just flagging which mean we don't have to resolve it now. When the game got bigger, SkillName shouldn't be string, since the string is prone to error.\r\nBetter use Enum, or SO later.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** Agreed, and matches this project's own \"don't design for hypothetical future requirements\" rule — there is currently exactly one skill behavior (the empowered hit), so an enum or SO here would enumerate a set of one. Logged as a forward-looking item in `Skill.md`'s Open Questions table rather than acted on now — flag me when a second distinct skill behavior is actually being designed.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED (deferred, as requested).** Added to `Skill.md`'s Open Questions table: \"Should `SkillName` become an enum or SO instead of a hand-typed string?\" — not acted on, revisit when a second skill behavior exists."
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Data/HeroDataSO.cs",
      "description": "Could we group them as GuardRail? Use class, struct, or something.\r\n\r\nThis is to add readability.\r\nIs that make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** Makes sense — right now the four floors (`MinMaxHP`, `MinDefense`, `MinAttackSpeed`, `MinSkillMultiplier`) are just four loose `private const` fields that happen to sit next to each other; nothing in the code says \"these four are a matched set that exists for the same reason.\" Grouping them into a small nested static class (e.g. `private static class Guardrails`) would make that relationship explicit and is a pure rename/restructure with no behavior change — a candidate for the fast lane we just set up (mechanical-only changes can skip the pre-code GDD read). This is your call to greenlight, not something I'll do unprompted.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** Grouped into a nested `private static class Guardrails` holding all four consts; every `[Range(...)]` attribute and the `OnValidate()` clamps now reference `Guardrails.MinMaxHP` etc."
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Data/HeroDataSO.cs",
      "description": "This is just asking, when does this method run?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** `OnValidate()` is a Unity callback that fires automatically, in the Editor only, any time this asset's serialized fields change — editing a value in the Inspector, dragging in a new reference, undo/redo, or the asset being reimported. It never runs in a built player and isn't on any kind of timer or per-frame loop; it's purely reactive to an Inspector edit. That's exactly why it's used here as the safety net for hand-typed values (see the comment two lines above it, and the Authoring Guardrails table in `Hero.md`).\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED (informational — no action needed).**"
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Data/HeroDataSO.cs",
      "description": "Could we rename this to HeroDataSO?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** Doable, but not for free — `TraitData` is also a `ScriptableObject` in this same codebase and doesn't carry an \"SO\" suffix, so renaming only `HeroData` would split the convention rather than establish one. My recommendation: either rename both (`HeroData` → `HeroDataSO`, `TraitData` → `TraitDataSO`) for consistency, or leave both as-is — a lone `HeroDataSO` next to a bare `TraitData` would read as arbitrary to the next person who opens both files. Your call which way to go.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** Renamed both: `HeroData` → `HeroDataSO`, `TraitData` → `TraitDataSO`. This file is now `HeroDataSO.cs`."
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/HeroDataRuntime.cs",
      "description": "Could we rename this to \"HeroDataRuntime\"?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** I'd push back on this one. \"Combatant\" is already the established name for exactly this pairing across the whole doc set — `Combat.md`, `Hero.md`, `Skill.md`, and `Trait.md` all reference \"Combatant\" by name in their Core Rules, and the reading-guide doc frames the whole design around \"HeroData (authored) / Combatant (runtime)\" as the central thing to understand. Renaming it to `HeroDataRuntime` would (1) touch more doc surface than the `AutoBattleResolver` rename we just did, since every GDD's Core Rules reference it directly, and (2) be slightly misleading — a `Combatant` built for the enemy team is still a `Combatant`, not \"hero data\"; the name currently carries no team bias, which matches how enemies are built from the same `HeroData` assets today. I'd keep `Combatant` unless there's a reason beyond naming symmetry with `HeroData`.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED — renamed after all, on different grounds than first proposed.** Extended back-and-forth landed on keeping \"Hero\" as the project's primary noun (not switching to a broader \"Unit\" umbrella, since a real Hero/Summon/non-Hero-Enemy type split doesn't exist in code yet — logged as an Open Question in `Hero.md`), with a shared `HeroData` root + pipeline-stage suffix for all three classes: `HeroDataSO` / `HeroDataSeed` / `HeroDataRuntime`. This file is now `HeroDataRuntime.cs`. Full reasoning in `.tours/deferred-design-questions.tour`'s last step."
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/HeroDataRuntime.cs",
      "description": "These comment shouldn't be here, no?\r\n\r\nMove it to where their logic are.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** Agreed — this file has no methods besides two computed properties; it's a passive data bag. The two-clock explanation describes simulation *behavior* (how `AttackCooldown`/`MoveCooldown` are charged and clamped), and that logic lives entirely in the manager's `BattleLoop()`. I'd move the full explanation to sit directly above the charge/clamp code there, and leave just a one-line pointer on these two fields here (\"see the manager's `BattleLoop()` for how these are charged/clamped\"). Low-risk, no behavior change — say the word and I'll make the move.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** Full explanation moved to sit above Phase 1 in `BattleLoop()`; this file now carries a one-line pointer on `AttackCooldown`/`MoveCooldown` instead. (That method lived on `AutoBattleSimulator.cs` at the time; the manager was later renamed to `AutoChessManager.cs` — see `.tours/autobattlesimreview.tour`.)"
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Data/BattleData.cs",
      "description": "This is also confusing.\r\nFrom what I get, this is a class to remember which hex position a unit is standing on.\r\nThen, why would it need Icon, Tint, Range, etc...\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** `CombatantSnapshot` is broader than a position-tracker — per the comment two lines above it, it's \"the view's ONLY source of unit appearance,\" the full read-only contract `BattleBoardManager`/`BattleHUD` use to draw a unit without ever touching `HeroData` directly (that no-hardcoded-lookup rule is Hero.md Core Rule 7). `Position` is one field among several for the same reason `Icon`/`Tint`/`Range`/`MaxHP`/`CurrentHP` are all here — the view needs all of them to render one unit, full stop. The real fix is probably the lead-in comment, not the class: it should open with \"everything the view needs to draw one unit\" rather than reading like a position wrapper that happens to also carry other fields. Want me to reword it?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** `CombatantSnapshot`'s lead-in comment in `BattleData.cs` now opens with \"Everything the view needs to draw one unit — position included, but not the point of the class\" instead of reading like a position wrapper."
    }
  ]
}